---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
import Header from '../components/Header.astro';
import Footer from '../components/Footer.astro';

const lang = 'en' as const;
---

<Layout
  title="What's new in SoloMD v2.3 — semantic search & WYSIWYG live edit"
  description="v2.3 adds local semantic search (⌘⇧F, on-device, no model download) and a fourth WYSIWYG live edit view mode. Combined with v2.2's MCP server, AutoGit history and 14 AI providers — all shipped, all in core."
  lang={lang}
>
  <Header lang={lang} />
  <main>
    <article class="container whats-new">
      <nav class="breadcrumbs">
        <a href="/">Home</a> / <span>What's new</span>
      </nav>

      <p class="version-row">
        <span class="version-tag">v2.3</span>
        <time>April 2026</time>
      </p>
      <h1>What's new in v2.3</h1>
      <p class="lead">
        Two changes that move the goalposts for "what a Markdown editor
        ships in core" — <strong>local semantic search</strong> and a
        <strong>WYSIWYG live edit</strong> view mode. Both stack on top
        of v2.2's MCP server, AutoGit history, and 14 AI providers.
        Everything below is in core, MIT-licensed, and works without an
        account.
      </p>

      <section>
        <h2>🔍 Local semantic search (v2.3)</h2>
        <p>
          Press <kbd>⌘⇧F</kbd>. A new search panel ranks paragraphs by
          meaning instead of just keywords — type <em>"deployment"</em>
          and you'll surface notes about <em>"rolling out"</em>,
          <em>"shipping"</em>, <em>"cutting a release"</em>.
        </p>
        <p>The interesting part is what it doesn't do:</p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>No model file download.</strong> The bundled embedder is a hashed character-trigram function that runs entirely in our Rust process. No 100 MB ONNX file, no first-launch download.</li>
          <li><strong>No network call, ever.</strong> Query embeds locally; ranking is brute-force cosine similarity in Rust over a SQLite store. The query text never touches a socket.</li>
          <li><strong>Off by default.</strong> Settings → "Enable semantic search" turns it on. Until then nothing is scanned and no index file is created.</li>
          <li><strong>Index lives in the workspace.</strong> <code>&lt;workspace&gt;/.solomd/embeddings.sqlite</code>, auto-added to <code>.gitignore</code> so AutoGit won't snapshot embeddings.</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          Field-wide gap closer: Obsidian's semantic search lives behind
          paid plugins (Smart Connections etc.) and most of those call
          hosted embedding APIs. Typora and MarkText don't have it at all.
          Tolaria doesn't either. SoloMD is the only one shipping it in
          core, fully offline.
        </p>
        <p class="callout">
          See <a href="/security/">Security § 5: Local RAG / semantic search</a> for the full data-flow writeup.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>✍️ WYSIWYG live edit mode (v2.3)</h2>
        <p>
          A fourth view mode joins source / split / preview:
          <strong>live edit</strong>. Headings render larger inline,
          <code>**bold**</code> shows bold without the asterisks, lists
          indent visually, blockquotes get a left border. The markup
          reveals when the caret enters the line — so you always have
          a way back to source without switching modes.
        </p>
        <p>
          Toggle from the view-mode switcher in the editor header, or
          via the command palette (<kbd>⌘⇧K</kbd> → "Live edit").
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>From v2.2 — already shipped</h2>
        <p>If you missed v2.2, here's the gist:</p>

        <h3>📜 AutoGit version history</h3>
        <p>
          One toggle in Settings. From that moment, every <kbd>⌘S</kbd>
          becomes a snapshot in a local <code>.git</code> inside your
          workspace. The right-hand history panel lists every commit
          that touched the active file; click <strong>Restore</strong>
          to roll back atomically. libgit2 vendored — no system git
          required. Never auto-pushed.
        </p>

        <h3>🔌 MCP server</h3>
        <p>
          1.5 MB sidecar binary. Point Claude Desktop, Cursor, or Codex
          CLI at your workspace and it gets 8 read tools out of the
          box (<code>list_notes</code>, <code>read_note</code>,
          <code>search</code>, <code>get_backlinks</code>,
          <code>list_tags</code>, <code>get_outline</code>, etc.) plus
          2 write tools gated behind <code>--allow-write</code>.
          stdio only — no network port. Path-traversal guarded.
        </p>

        <h3>🤖 AI rewrite — 14 BYOK providers</h3>
        <p>
          <kbd>⌘J</kbd> on a selection. Pick rewrite / shorten / expand /
          translate (en+zh) / explain / custom. OpenAI, Anthropic,
          Gemini, xAI, Mistral, Groq, DeepSeek, Qwen, GLM, Moonshot,
          Doubao, SiliconFlow, OpenRouter, Ollama. Keys live in the OS
          keychain. Direct vendor calls, no relay.
        </p>
      </section>

      <section>
        <h2>What's still on the table</h2>
        <p>
          The honest list of things SoloMD doesn't do yet:
        </p>
        <ul>
          <li><strong>Built-in CRDT sync</strong> — the v3 anchor. For now use iCloud Drive / Dropbox / Syncthing, or AutoGit + push manually.</li>
          <li><strong>Mobile</strong> — iOS App Store submission is in review. No Android.</li>
          <li><strong>Plugin system</strong> — intentionally not on the roadmap. The features serious writers ask for keep landing in core instead.</li>
          <li><strong>Wiki-style backlinks / graph view</strong> — Obsidian territory. SoloMD is a writing tool, not a knowledge graph.</li>
        </ul>
      </section>

      <section class="cta">
        <p>
          <a class="btn btn--primary" href="https://github.com/zhitongblog/solomd/releases">Download v2.3 →</a>
          &nbsp;
          <a class="btn" href="/blog/v2-2-mcp-autogit-and-14-ai-providers/">Read the v2.2 deep-dive</a>
        </p>
        <p class="note">
          MIT-licensed. No account. No telemetry by default. Audit the source on
          <a href="https://github.com/zhitongblog/solomd" rel="external">GitHub</a>.
        </p>
      </section>
    </article>
  </main>
  <Footer lang={lang} />
</Layout>

<style>
  .whats-new { max-width: 820px; padding: 40px 20px 80px; }
  .breadcrumbs { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted, #8a8a8a); margin-bottom: 16px; }
  .breadcrumbs a { color: inherit; }
  .version-row { display: flex; align-items: center; gap: 12px; margin: 8px 0 4px; }
  .version-tag { display: inline-block; padding: 4px 12px; border-radius: 999px; background: #ff9f40; color: #000; font-weight: 700; font-size: 12px; letter-spacing: 0.04em; font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace; }
  .whats-new time { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted, #888); }
  .whats-new h1 { font-size: 2.4rem; line-height: 1.15; margin: 0 0 18px; }
  .whats-new h2 { font-size: 1.6rem; margin: 44px 0 14px; }
  .whats-new h3 { font-size: 1.15rem; margin: 22px 0 8px; }
  .whats-new .lead { font-size: 1.15rem; color: var(--text-muted, #555); line-height: 1.65; margin-bottom: 24px; }
  .whats-new p { line-height: 1.75; margin: 12px 0; }
  .whats-new ul { padding-left: 22px; }
  .whats-new li { margin: 6px 0; line-height: 1.7; }
  .whats-new code { background: #f5f5f0; padding: 2px 6px; border-radius: 4px; font-size: 0.9em; }
  .whats-new kbd { background: #f5f5f0; border: 1px solid #ddd; border-radius: 3px; padding: 1px 6px; font-family: ui-monospace, Menlo, monospace; font-size: 0.85em; }
  .whats-new a { color: #ff9f40; }
  .whats-new .callout { background: #fff7ee; border-left: 3px solid #ff9f40; padding: 10px 16px; margin: 18px 0; border-radius: 0 6px 6px 0; font-size: 0.95em; }
  .whats-new .cta { margin-top: 44px; padding-top: 28px; border-top: 1px solid #eee; }
  .whats-new .cta .note { font-size: 13px; color: var(--text-muted, #888); margin-top: 12px; }
  .btn { display: inline-block; padding: 10px 22px; border-radius: 8px; text-decoration: none; font-weight: 600; color: var(--text); }
  .btn--primary { background: #ff9f40; color: #000 !important; }
</style>
